{
  "text": "The phylogenetic results obtained in this study differ from those presented earlier by [CITATION_1] . Based on their molecular and morphological data at least three melithaeid genera could be validated: Acabaria, Melithaea and Mopsella. Based on our molecular phylogenies these results are not supported. In our case, the phylogenetic results indicate that four genera are paraphyletic, and have been reorganized into the single genus Melithaea. The difference in results between our study and Aguilar- [CITATION_2] are most probably the result of a sampling bias. Although the sampling was limited to Japan, comparison between the phylogenetic tree by [CITATION_3] and the phylogenies presented herein show similar, basal topologies. For example, clade A which predominantly consists of Acabaria spp. resembles the clade containing Acabaria sp. A-D in [CITATION_4] . Consequently, Clade B is comparable to the clades containing Mopsella and Melithaea spp. in [CITATION_5] . Clade B in our phylogenies is also predominantly composed of Mopsella and Melithaea spp. [CITATION_6] sampled solely from tropical Japanese reefs, which automatically excludes species and genera primarily occurring in the Indian Ocean and Red Sea. It therefore appears that intensive sampling of Melithaeidae in a relatively small biogeographic area biases the subsequent molecular phylogenies and as a result different conclusions are reached.",
